Hong Kong Style Spaghetti Bolognese 肉醬意粉 ft. @ottogiamerica 🍝

One of my favorite things to get at a 茶餐厅 :’) A slightly sweet savory bolognese sauce with spaghetti 👩🏻‍🍳😚 My mom would always tell me not to order this at restaurants cause she can make it at home but she never made it HAHA. Maybe that’s why I like it as much as I do now.

Ingredients:
+ 1 lb ground beef
+ 1 medium carrot (diced)
+ 1/2 onion (diced)
+ ~3 cloves garlic (minced)
+ 1 tomato (diced)
+ 1/2T cooking oil
+ 1/2t sugar
+ 1/2t salt
+ 1/4t black pepper
+ 3T tomato paste
+ 1 cup chicken broth
+ 1/2 cup water
+ 1.5t maggi sauce
+ 1t dark soy sauce
+ 2t worcestershire sauce
+ 2T Ottogi ketchup
+ 2-4 bay leaves
+ ~3 servings of spaghetti
+ 2T butter
+ shredded mozzarella cheese (to your liking)

Steps:
1. Chop up your tomato, onion, garlic, and carrots, then set aside.
2. In a pan over medium heat, add cooking oil, then add in carrots and onions. Stir fry til onions are slightly translucent. 
3. Add in your ground beef and separate into small pieces with your spatula/spoon. Stir fry all together and add garlic, salt, sugar, and black pepper.
4. Once ground beef is mostly cooked, add tomato paste and stir fry it for about a minute til it slightly caramelizes.
5. Add in tomato and stir fry together, before adding chicken broth and water. 
6. Once simmering, add in maggi sauce, worcestershire sauce, dark soy sauce, Ottogi ketchup, and bay leaves. Stir well and let simmer for ~10 minutes.
7. Cook spaghetti according to package instructions in a pot of salted water. Once cooked, drain spaghetti and set aside.
8. Once sauce is done simmering, add butter and stir to melt in.
9. In an oven safe dish, mix spaghetti noodles with 90% of the sauce before adding a layer of the remaining sauce on top.
10. Sprinkle mozzarella on top and broil til melted/slightly golden brown. Enjoy!

Hong Kong Style Mango Pancake 芒果班戟 ft. @mangoboard 🥭

#ad An absolute classic Hong Kong style dessert that you can’t go wrong with. A soft pancake pillow enveloping a cloud of whipped cream and ripe juicy mango. ☁️ Having fresh mango is probably one of my favorite ways to up my Vitamin C, along with Vitamin A and fiber, but maybe I’m biased since mango is my favorite fruit. :’)

Check out more ways to enjoy mangos on www.mango.org !

#mango #alwaysmangoszn #mmmangos #mangoParty #mangopancake #mangodessert
#hongkongstyledessert

Ingredients:
+ 2 eggs 
+ 1/2 cup cake flour
+ 3/4 cup milk
+ 1 3/4 tablespoon sugar
+ 1 tablespoon cooking oil
+ a few drops of yellow food coloring or a sprinkle of turmeric powder
+ 3 ripe mangos
+ 3/4 cup whipping cream
+ 3/4 tablespoon sugar
+ 1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract
+ 1/2T cooking oil (for cooking the pancake)

Steps:
1. Crack eggs into a medium-sized bowl and beat. Add milk, then whisk to combine.
2. Sift cake flour into the same bowl, add sugar, and then whisk until smooth and runny.
3. Add cooking oil and your preferred yellow food dye (A few drops of yellow food coloring or a sprinkle of turmeric powder), then whisk to combine.
4. Wash mangos, and cut into 3 parts lengthwise. (2 sides and seed part) Then scoop out the mango side parts from the skin with a metal spoon. Cut into a rectangular shape. 
5. Spread a thin layer of cooking oil with a tissue onto a nonstick pan over low heat. Spread a spoonful of
batter onto the pan and spread to cover the pan. When air bubbles form, remove from the pan and put aside. Be sure not to flip it.  
6. Add whipping cream, vanilla extract, and sugar into a bowl and whip until stiff peaks form.
7. On a clean surface, lay a pancake smooth side down. Add a dollop of whipped cream, a piece of mango, and if preferred, a little more whipped cream on top. Then gently fold the sides on top of each other, with the other sides following, forming a sealed pillow. (Try not to squeeze the cream).
8. Recommended: Refrigerate for 30 minutes before serving.

Mango Filled Croissant Taiyaki 🥭🐟 ft. @mangoboard 

#ad I remember when I first tried this a year ago, I was mind-blown at how good it was. It’s such a simple fusion (basically just a fish-shaped pastry), but absolutely genius and made to perfection with the caramelized exterior of the croissant and the delicious, fresh mango filling.

I swear mangos are one of the most versatile fruits, it incorporates well with everything you want to eat, whether it’s a sweet or savory dish. Mangos are also health-promoting superfruits, so we love them for that. Check out more ways to enjoy mangos on www.mango.org !

Ingredients:
• 1 large mango
• 1-2 teaspoons sugar (mango filling)
• 1/4 cup sugar (coating puff pastry)
• 8 square puff pastry sheets

Steps:
1. Cut a mango lengthwise into 3 parts, 2 side parts, and 1 seed part. Then use a metal spoon to scoop mango out into a bowl.
2. Add sugar according to taste and ripeness of mango, then cut up mango into smaller pieces. With a fork or whisk, mash up the mango until a lumpy filling is formed. (Don’t blend into a puree because you want to make sure there’s still some texture in the filling)
3. Onto a plate, add sugar and spread into an even layer. Take each square puff pastry sheet and coat one side of the square in sugar. (For convenience, I folded them in half beforehand)
4. Preheat your taiyaki maker, then begin to assemble your croissant taiyaki. Begin with the square puff pastry sheet as the first layer with the sugar-coated side on the outside. Then add mango filling within the fish shape, fold the remaining puff pastry over, and press the edges lightly to ensure a sealed teriyaki.
5. Cook croissant taiyaki till golden brown. (Each maker can differ in cooking times)
6. Once ready, remove them with tongs or chopsticks, set aside to cool for a few minutes (if preferred) and enjoy!

Mango Egg Tarts 芒果蛋撻🥭 ft. @mangoboard 

A refreshing twist on one of my all-time favorite desserts. Yet another Hong Kong classic combined with my favorite superfruit, mango #ad! I love how the mango compliments the egg custard and cuts the sweetness with a little bit of tartness! 🥭

Such an easy way to spice up your classic egg tarts with a nutritious health-promoting fruit 😎 Check out more ways to enjoy mangos on www.mango.org !

Ingredients:
• 2 eggs
• 1/4 cup sugar
• 2/3 hot water
• 1/3 cup evaporated milk
• 1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
• puff pastry egg tart shells
• 2 mangos
• ~1 tablespoon sugar
 
Steps:
1. Mix sugar and hot water in a bowl till completely dissolved, then let it cool on the side.
2. In another bowl, whisk the eggs till beat and add evaporated milk.
3. Pour in the sugar water and vanilla extract then mix.
4. Strain the egg custard mixture to get rid of any foam into a measuring cup, set aside.
5. Cut 2 mangos lengthwise into 3 parts, 2 side parts and 1 seed part. Score cubes in each side part and scoop mango out into a bowl with a metal spoon.
6. Cut off remaining mango on the seed part into the bowl.
7. With a whisk or metal fork, mash up the cubed mango in the bowl.
8. Add sugar according to taste and ripeness of the mango.
9. Preheat oven to 390 °F.
10. Take out puff pastry egg tart shells and add a small layer of mango filling. Then fill the rest of the shell up to 90% with egg custard mixture.
11. Bake on the lowest rack for 30 minutes at 390 °F or till the top of the egg tart begins to blister slightly.
12. Remove from the oven, let cool, and enjoy!

Korean Style Corn Dogs 🧀 ft. @ottogiamerica 

One of my favorite snacks to get in NYC :’) The cheese pull never fails and I love the crispy, soft, chewy, exterior. 😎

Ingredients:
Dough—
+ 1 cup lukewarm water
+ 2T sugar
+ 1 pack dry yeast (~2t)
+ 1/2t kosher salt
+ 1 3/4 cup all purpose flour

Other:
+3 hotdogs
+3 mozzarella cheese sticks
+Ottogi panko
+Ottogi soybean oil
+Ottogi ketchup
+mustard
+sugar (optional)

Steps:
1. In a large bowl, add water, sugar, yeast and mix well. Let sit for 1-2 minutes for yeast to activate.
2. Add salt and flour and mix well, til a somewhat smooth dough forms. Then cover and let sit for an hour or til it doubles in size.
3. Cut hot dogs and cheese sticks in halves.
4. Skewer the hotdog half first, then add the cheese stick on top. Repeat with the rest and finish by coating with some flour.
5. Pour oil into a large deep pan / pot and heat until it’s 320#koreanstyleF or until the chopstick bubbles. (Be sure your oil is not too hot so your corndogs don’t burn)
5. Cover with dough and coat in panko.
6. Place corn dogs in the oil and fry for 6-7 minutes, til golden brown. (I rotated and basted mine since I was frying in more shallow oil)
7. Optional: coat with sugar
8. Drizzle with ketchup, mustard, and whatever condiments you’d like! Enjoy 😋

Air-fryer Char Siu Chicken 🍗

A super simple recipe with a lil twist from the traditional pork version that works great for meal prepping too! 🍴

If you want to go the more traditional method, you can replace the food coloring with red fermented bean curds!

Ingredients:
+ 1T garlic
+ 1/2T ginger
+ scallion (for garnish)
+ 1T honey
+ 2T soy sauce
+ 1T dark soy sauce
+ 1T oyster sauce
+ 2T brown sugar
+ 1t five spice powder
+ 1T shaoxing wine
+ white pepper
+ few drops red food coloring

Steps:
1. Cut garlic, ginger, and scallion. 
2. Mix soy sauce, dark soy sauce, honey, oyster sauce, brown sugar, five spice powder, shaoxing wine, white pepper, and food coloring together in a bowl.
3. Mix 2 chicken thighs with the marinade well. Then cover and marinate for ~1-2 hours, best overnight. 
4. Air fry skin-side down at 375°F for ~11 minutes. Brush on more marinade, flip, brush marinade again on the skin, and air fry skin-side up for 6-8 minutes. Or until edges are charred. 
5. Let sit for a few minutes before chopping into slices.
6. Serve with fresh rice, some leafy greens, and garnish with scallion and a drizzle of the reduced marinade.

Gamjatang 감자탕 (Korean Pork Bone Soup)

Hands down one of my favorite stews. Seriously can’t go wrong w/ fall off the bone pork 😩 I could eat this every day + wouldn’t get sick of it.

Thank you @maangchi for blessing us with this recipe, queen never misses. 👸🏻

Ingredients: 
+ 2.5 to 3 lbs pork neck bones 
+ 1 oz ginger (sliced)
+ 2T doenjang (Korean fermented bean paste)
+ 2 dried Shiitake mushrooms
+ 1 medium onion (sliced in 1 in pieces)
+ 1 dried red chili pepper (or a few red chili peppers)
+ 1 lb napa cabbage (cores cut off + cut in quarters)
+ 2-3 medium potatoes (peeled + cut into chunks)
+ 8 oz soybean sprouts (rinsed)
+ 4 stalks scallion (cut into 2 in pieces)
+ 1 stalk scallion (diced, for garnish)
+ 8-12 perilla leaves (stems cut off, cut in half)

Seasoning Paste: 
+ 6 garlic cloves (minced)
+ 3T gochugaru 
+ 1T gochujang 
+ 3T fish sauce
+ ¼ cup perilla seeds powder (substitute: sesame seed powder - blended roasted sesame seeds w/ pinch of salt)
+ 1/2t ground black pepper
+ 1/4-1/2 cup water

Steps:
1. In a large bowl, rinse + soak pork neck bones in cold water for 30 minutes.
2. Cut napa cabbage into quarters + then cut off the cores.
3. Blanch napa cabbage in a large pot of boiling water for 1 min. Reserve water for pork bones. Rinse napa cabbage in cold water + tear pieces lengthwise.
5. Boil bones for 7 minutes in the same large pot with lid on, over medium high heat. Discard water, strain bones, + rinse each one in cold water.
6. Chop onion into pieces + ginger into slices.
7. In a large pot, add pork bones, onion, dried shiitake mushrooms, dried red chili pepper, doenjang (korean fermented bean paste), + water. Cook for 90 min, lid on, over med heat.
8. Rinse soybean sprouts, chop potatoes, scallion stalks, garlic, + perilla leaves. 
9. After 90 min, cut shiitake mushrooms + add back into stew.
10. Mix seasoning paste ingredients in a small bowl, then add to stew along w/ potatoes, napa cabbage, soybean sprouts, + scallion. Cook for 30-40 min, lid on, over med heat.
11. Add perilla leaves and serve w/ rice

Bok Choy Kimchi / Geotjeori 🥬🌶️

Tried this recipe as soon as I watched it on TikTok and my roommates and I have been making it for 3 weeks straight LOL. It’s soooo good. Refreshing, flavorful, and the perfect crisp from the bokchoy 🥬🌶️ 

Thanks @stellanspice for this holy grail recipe 😭🧎🏻‍♀️ Got me and my roommates in a chokehold fr. 

*Also as Stella mentioned in her blog and video, it’s technically a geotjeori/muchim, not kimchi since it’s not fermented! 

Ingredients: 
+ ~6 bulbs baby bok choy
+ 2T roasted sesame seeds (crushed)
+ 4T gochugaru
+ 2T rice vinegar (og recipe called for plum vinegar)
+ 2-3T sugar
+ 4t sesame oil
+ 4t fish sauce
+ 4 garlic cloves (minced) 

Steps:
1. Cut off the stems of bok choy and separate the leaves. Rinse the bok choy and shake off excess water.
2. Crush sesame seeds with a mortar and pestle or in a blender.
3. Add bok choy to a mixing bowl with the rest of the ingredients and mix well with gloves on or clean hands.
5. Serve immediately or store it in the refrigerator for a few hours before serving. Best eaten day of or within a few days!

Easy Scallion Pancake Wrap ft. @eat.mila 

Been seeing different variations of this all over my social media so had to throw in my take ‼️ Love how customizable it is 🤭 Made so easy and delicious with @eat.mila ‘s Dan Dan Noodles sauce and Chili Crisp Oil 😩🌶️

Ingredients:
+ 1 frozen scallion pancake 
+ 1T MìLà Dan Dan Noodle sauce 
+ 1t MìLà Chili Crisp Oil
+ julienned cucumber 
+ 1 egg (beat)
+ 1 stalk scallion (diced)
+ salt and pepper to taste

Steps:
1. Chop up scallion and cucumber, set aside.
2. Beat 1 egg in a small bowl, season w/ salt and pepper to taste.
3. Pan fry scallion pancake with some oil over medium heat til golden brown.
4. Slightly lift up the scallion pancake with a spatula, and pour in enough egg for the scallion pancake to sit on a thin layer. Then set the pancake back onto the pan and let the egg cook onto scallion pancake.
5. Boil the MìLà Dan Dan Noodle sauce packet in water for a few minutes. Cut packet open with scissors.
6. Scoop sauce onto the pancake, egg side up, spreading an even layer around. Then sprinkle the cucumber and scallion. Drizzle MìLà Chili Crisp Oil on top.
7. Roll up the scallion pancake into a wrap/roll, cut in half if preferred, and enjoy!

Absolute comfort food in the comfort of your own home and made so much easier with an airfryer‼️🫶🏻 It’s a superior Cantonese roast meat and can be used in a billion different types of dishes as well, so we love 😎 

Ingredients:

+ 1T garlic
+ 1/2T ginger
+ 1.5T honey
+ 2T soy sauce
+ 1T dark soy sauce
+ 1T oyster sauce
+ 2T brown sugar
+ 1t five spice powder
+ 1T shaoxing wine
+ white pepper
+ 1 cube red fermented tofu/few drops red food coloring

Steps:
1. Chop garlic and ginger roughly. 
2. Mix garlic, ginger, soy sauce, dark soy sauce, honey, oyster sauce, brown sugar, five spice powder, shaoxing wine, white pepper, and red fermented tofu/food coloring together in a bowl.
3. Mix pork with the marinade well. Then cover and marinate for at least 6 hours or best overnight.
4. Air fry at  400°F for ~13-15 minutes. Flip every 4-5 minutes, first time, baste with more marinade, and for the last two, baste with honey.
5. Let sit for a 10 minutes before chopping into slices.
6. Serve with fresh rice, some leafy greens, an egg, and drizzle w/ the reduced marinade and enjoy!

Ingredients:
+ 1 pack frozen udon
+ 1/4 cup soy sauce
+ 1/4 cup mirin
+ 1.5t sugar
+ 3 cups dashi stock
+ 2 Japanese curry cubes
+ 1/2 small onion (diced)
+ 3-4 strips of thinly sliced beef/pork belly

Steps:

Chicken Marinade:
+ 3 cloves garlic (minced)
+ 2T soy sauce
+ 2T dark soy sauce
+ 1/2T five spice powder 
+ 1/2-1T honey/brown sugar
+ 1/2t sesame oil

+ 2 boneless, skin on, chicken thighs

Bokchoy:
+ 2-3 heads bok choy
+ 1-2 cloves garlic (sliced)

Steps:

5. Airfry chicken in a separate basket at 375°F for ~10-13 min and bok choy at 370°F for ~5 min or until cooked well.
6. Serve chicken and bok choy with fresh rice, garnish with scallion, and drizzle chicken with the leftover sauce in the airfryer. Enjoy!
